  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      MRI imaging in clinically evident inguinal hernia is not routinely used. In other painful
      inguinal conditions (such as sportsmans hernia) inflammatory changes have been detected. The
      aim of the present study is to determine, whether similar inflammatory changes can be
      detected with MRI scan in inguinal hernia. Also, patient questionaires are used
      preoperatively and postoperatively to determine, if preoperative pain scores can be used as a
      predictive value for postoperative prolonged pain/neuralgia.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
